TRGAted App: Multiple Variate Analysis

Nick Borcherding

6/3/2018

Set Up

The goal of this tutorial is basic multivariate analysis using the reverse-phase protein array (RPPA) data and clinical variables available in the TRGAted application. We will start with looping across clinical variables as single covariates. Preceeding to mutlivariate analysis using categorical clinical variables.

Load Libraries

library(survMisc)
## Loading required package: survival
library(ggplot2)

library(survminer)

Load Cancer Data

This could be any .csv file located in the TRGAted github repository.

cancerType <- read.csv("~/TRGAted/BRCA.csv")

Analysis

Survival analysis looping across multiple variables

Here we are going to examine the difference in overall survival outcomes based on the HER2 versus basal (or basal-like) subtypes of breast cancer.

Setting the variables of interest - time, the respective survival indicator for selected time (ind), and clinical variables (covariates).

#Slecting the survival and time variables of interest
time = cancerType[,"DSS.time"] #diseas-specific survival
ind = cancerType[,"DSS"]

#Selecting the clincal variables of interest
covariates <- c("subtype","ajcc_pathologic_tumor_stage", "histological_type")

Looping over Cox regression for each individual variable, this is a good first step before multivariate analysis that allows for better selection of clinical variables.

### loop through each variable
for (i in 1:length(covariates)){
    print(covariates[i])
    print(coxph(Surv(time, ind) ~ get(covariates[i]), data=cancerType))
}

We can visualize the survival difference calculated above, but making a survival curve. Here we will look at tumor stage information, however, this can be changed for any variable by modifying the fit model.

fit <- survfit(Surv(time, ind) ~ ajcc_pathologic_tumor_stage, #modify the variables in the model
               data = cancerType) 

ggsurvplot(fit, data = cancerType,
                tables.y.text = FALSE,
                tables.theme = theme_cleantable(),
                xlab = "Time in days",
                pval = T,
                pval.coord = c(0.05, 0.05),
                legend.labs = c("Stage I", "Stage II", "Stage III", "Stage IV"),
                risk.table = TRUE, 
                fontsize = 5,
                ggtheme = theme_bw(base_family = "sans", base_size = 12))

Another way to visualize the aareg function - Aalen additive regression model (aareg). More information can be found at the function information.. We will input the same variables we are interested in using a similar equation to the coxph model. The function and subsequent autoplotting of aareg shows the how the effect of the covariate changes over time.

aa_fit <-aareg(Surv(time, ind) ~ subtype+ajcc_pathologic_tumor_stage+histological_type , 
                 data = cancerType)
autoplot(aa_fit)

summary(aa_fit)

Analysis using protein-level data from RPPA

Clinical variables are more straight forward when it comes to multivariate analysis, they are categorical. RPPA values available in the TRGAted application are continuous and transformed using z-scores. To begin, we will need to identify the protein or proteins of interest, select a cut-off, and convert them to categorical variables. We are going to select proteins that are tested via immunohistochemistry as part of a standard work-up for breast cancer diagnosis and treatment.

time = "DSS.time" #diseas-specific survival
ind = "DSS"
proteins <- c("ERALPHA", "PR", "HER2")

cut <- surv_cutpoint(cancerType, time=time, event=ind, variables=proteins)
cat <- surv_categorize(cut)
rownames(cat) <- cancerType$patient
cat[1:10,1:5]
##              DSS.time DSS ERALPHA   PR HER2
## TCGA-3C-AALI     4005   0     low high high
## TCGA-3C-AALK     1448   0     low high high
## TCGA-4H-AAAK      348   0    high high high
## TCGA-5L-AAT1     1471   0    high high high
## TCGA-5T-A9QA      303   0    high high high
## TCGA-A1-A0SF     1463   0    high high high
## TCGA-A1-A0SH     1437   0     low high high
## TCGA-A1-A0SJ      416   0     low high high
## TCGA-A1-A0SK      967   1     low  low  low
## TCGA-A1-A0SO      852   0     low  low high

We now have the samples categorized into high or low groupings for each protein. We next need to add our other clinical variables of interest.

cat <- cbind.data.frame(cat, cancerType$subtype, cancerType$ajcc_pathologic_tumor_stage, cancerType$histological_type)
colnames(cat)[6] <- "subtype"
colnames(cat)[7] <- "tumor_stage"
colnames(cat)[8] <- "histological_type"

Now we can update our equation from above to include our new data frame, cat, with both our proteins and clinical variables of interest.

MVmodel2 <- coxph(Surv(DSS.time, DSS) ~ERALPHA+PR+HER2+subtype+tumor_stage+histological_type, data=cat)
## Warning in fitter(X, Y, strats, offset, init, control, weights = weights, :
## Loglik converged before variable 7,12,13 ; beta may be infinite.
summary(MVmodel2)

Conclusions

Hopefully this helps users start multivariate analysis using the RPPA datasets embedded in the TRGAted application. Multivariate analysis is complex and prone to a number of biases, if you are in doubt with how to perform an analysis or assess which model is superior, we suggest you consult a statistician at your institution. If you have anymore questions, feel free to email us.
